FB.AST.NPER.ZS-assets.def: Bank nonperforming loans to total gross loans are the value of nonperforming loans divided by the total value of the loan portfolio (including nonperforming loans before the deduction of specific loan-loss provisions). The loan amount recorded as nonperforming should be the gross value of the loan as recorded on the balance sheet, not just the amount that is overdue.
FB.AST.NPER.ZS-assets.name: Bank nonperforming loans to total gross loans
FB.AST.NPER.ZS-assets.source: International Monetary Fund, Financial Soundness Indicators.
FB.AST.NPER.ZS-assets.dataset: International Monetary Fund, Financial Soundness Indicators.

FB.BNK.CAPA.ZS-assets.def: Bank capital to assets is the ratio of bank capital and reserves to total assets. Capital and reserves include funds contributed by owners, retained earnings, general and special reserves, provisions, and valuation adjustments. Capital includes tier 1 capital (paid-up shares and common stock), which is a common feature in all countries' banking systems, and total regulatory capital, which includes several specified types of subordinated debt instruments that need not be repaid if the funds are required to maintain minimum capital levels (these comprise tier 2 and tier 3 capital). Total assets include all nonfinancial and financial assets.
FB.BNK.CAPA.ZS-assets.name: Bank capital to assets ratio
FB.BNK.CAPA.ZS-assets.source: International Monetary Fund, Financial Soundness Indicators.
FB.BNK.CAPA.ZS-assets.dataset: International Monetary Fund, Financial Soundness Indicators.

FD.AST.PRVT.GD.ZS-assets.def: Domestic credit to private sector by banks refers to financial resources provided to the private sector by other depository corporations (deposit taking corporations except central banks), such as through loans, purchases of nonequity securities, and trade credits and other accounts receivable, that establish a claim for repayment. For some countries these claims include credit to public enterprises.
FD.AST.PRVT.GD.ZS-assets.name: Domestic credit to private sector by banks
FD.AST.PRVT.GD.ZS-assets.source: International Monetary Fund, International Financial Statistics and data files, and World Bank and OECD GDP estimates.
FD.AST.PRVT.GD.ZS-assets.dataset: International Monetary Fund, International Financial Statistics and data files, and World Bank and OECD GDP estimates.

FD.RES.LIQU.AS.ZS-assets.def: Ratio of bank liquid reserves to bank assets is the ratio of domestic currency holdings and deposits with the monetary authorities to claims on other governments, nonfinancial public enterprises, the private sector, and other banking institutions.
FD.RES.LIQU.AS.ZS-assets.name: Bank liquid reserves to bank assets ratio
FD.RES.LIQU.AS.ZS-assets.source: International Monetary Fund, International Financial Statistics and data files.
FD.RES.LIQU.AS.ZS-assets.dataset: International Monetary Fund, International Financial Statistics and data files.

FM.AST.CGOV.ZG.M3-assets.def: Claims on central government (IFS line 32AN..ZK) include loans to central government institutions net of deposits.
FM.AST.CGOV.ZG.M3-assets.name: Claims on central government
FM.AST.CGOV.ZG.M3-assets.source: International Monetary Fund, International Financial Statistics and data files.
FM.AST.CGOV.ZG.M3-assets.dataset: International Monetary Fund, International Financial Statistics and data files.
FM.AST.CGOV.ZG.M3-assets.dim: annual growth as % of broad money
FM.AST.CGOV.ZG.M3-assets.units: annual growth as % of broad money

FM.AST.DOMO.ZG.M3-assets.def: Claims on other sectors of the domestic economy (IFS line 32S..ZK) include gross credit from the financial system to households, nonprofit institutions serving households, nonfinancial corporations, state and local governments, and social security funds.
FM.AST.DOMO.ZG.M3-assets.name: Claims on other sectors of the domestic economy
FM.AST.DOMO.ZG.M3-assets.source: International Monetary Fund, International Financial Statistics and data files.
FM.AST.DOMO.ZG.M3-assets.dataset: International Monetary Fund, International Financial Statistics and data files.
FM.AST.DOMO.ZG.M3-assets.dim: annual growth as % of broad money
FM.AST.DOMO.ZG.M3-assets.units: annual growth as % of broad money

FM.AST.DOMS.CN-assets.def: Net domestic credit is the sum of net claims on the central government and claims on other sectors of the domestic economy (IFS line 32). Data are in current local currency.
FM.AST.DOMS.CN-assets.name: Net domestic credit
FM.AST.DOMS.CN-assets.source: International Monetary Fund, International Financial Statistics and data files.
FM.AST.DOMS.CN-assets.dataset: International Monetary Fund, International Financial Statistics and data files.

FM.AST.NFRG.CN-assets.def: Net foreign assets are the sum of foreign assets held by monetary authorities and deposit money banks, less their foreign liabilities. Data are in current local currency.
FM.AST.NFRG.CN-assets.name: Net foreign assets
FM.AST.NFRG.CN-assets.source: International Monetary Fund, International Financial Statistics and data files.
FM.AST.NFRG.CN-assets.dataset: International Monetary Fund, International Financial Statistics and data files.

FM.AST.PRVT.GD.ZS-assets.def: Domestic credit to private sector refers to financial resources provided to the private sector, such as through loans, purchases of nonequity securities, and trade credits and other accounts receivable, that establish a claim for repayment. For some countries these claims include credit to public enterprises.
FM.AST.PRVT.GD.ZS-assets.name: Monetary Sector credit to private sector
FM.AST.PRVT.GD.ZS-assets.source: International Monetary Fund, International Financial Statistics and data files, and World Bank and OECD GDP estimates.
FM.AST.PRVT.GD.ZS-assets.dataset: International Monetary Fund, International Financial Statistics and data files, and World Bank and OECD GDP estimates.

FM.AST.PRVT.ZG.M3-assets.def: Claims on private sector (IFS line 32D..ZK or 32D..ZF) include gross credit from the financial system to individuals, enterprises, nonfinancial public entities not included under net domestic credit, and financial institutions not included elsewhere.
FM.AST.PRVT.ZG.M3-assets.name: Claims on private sector
FM.AST.PRVT.ZG.M3-assets.source: International Monetary Fund, International Financial Statistics and data files.
FM.AST.PRVT.ZG.M3-assets.dataset: International Monetary Fund, International Financial Statistics and data files.
FM.AST.PRVT.ZG.M3-assets.units: annual growth as % of broad money

FS.AST.CGOV.GD.ZS-assets.def: Claims on central government (IFS line 52AN or 32AN) include loans to central government institutions net of deposits.
FS.AST.CGOV.GD.ZS-assets.name: Claims on central government
FS.AST.CGOV.GD.ZS-assets.source: International Monetary Fund, International Financial Statistics and data files, and World Bank and OECD GDP estimates.
FS.AST.CGOV.GD.ZS-assets.dataset: International Monetary Fund, International Financial Statistics and data files, and World Bank and OECD GDP estimates.

FS.AST.DOMO.GD.ZS-assets.def: Claims on other sectors of the domestic economy (IFS line 52S or 32S) include gross credit from the financial system to households, nonprofit institutions serving households, nonfinancial corporations, state and local governments, and social security funds.
FS.AST.DOMO.GD.ZS-assets.name: Claims on other sectors of the domestic economy
FS.AST.DOMO.GD.ZS-assets.source: International Monetary Fund, International Financial Statistics and data files, and World Bank and OECD GDP estimates.
FS.AST.DOMO.GD.ZS-assets.dataset: International Monetary Fund, International Financial Statistics and data files, and World Bank and OECD GDP estimates.

FS.AST.DOMS.GD.ZS-assets.def: Domestic credit provided by the financial sector includes all credit to various sectors on a gross basis, with the exception of credit to the central government, which is net. The financial sector includes monetary authorities and deposit money banks, as well as other financial corporations where data are available (including corporations that do not accept transferable deposits but do incur such liabilities as time and savings deposits). Examples of other financial corporations are finance and leasing companies, money lenders, insurance corporations, pension funds, and foreign exchange companies.
FS.AST.DOMS.GD.ZS-assets.name: Domestic credit provided by financial sector
FS.AST.DOMS.GD.ZS-assets.source: International Monetary Fund, International Financial Statistics and data files, and World Bank and OECD GDP estimates.
FS.AST.DOMS.GD.ZS-assets.dataset: International Monetary Fund, International Financial Statistics and data files, and World Bank and OECD GDP estimates.

FS.AST.PRVT.GD.ZS-assets.def: Domestic credit to private sector refers to financial resources provided to the private sector by financial corporations, such as through loans, purchases of nonequity securities, and trade credits and other accounts receivable, that establish a claim for repayment. For some countries these claims include credit to public enterprises. The financial corporations include monetary authorities and deposit money banks, as well as other financial corporations where data are available (including corporations that do not accept transferable deposits but do incur such liabilities as time and savings deposits). Examples of other financial corporations are finance and leasing companies, money lenders, insurance corporations, pension funds, and foreign exchange companies.
FS.AST.PRVT.GD.ZS-assets.name: Domestic credit to private sector
FS.AST.PRVT.GD.ZS-assets.source: International Monetary Fund, International Financial Statistics and data files, and World Bank and OECD GDP estimates.
FS.AST.PRVT.GD.ZS-assets.dataset: International Monetary Fund, International Financial Statistics and data files, and World Bank and OECD GDP estimates.
